slidelink.displaytext: Field is the signature pedagogy of social work education

slidetranscripts.slidetranscript:
A lot of information - pay close attention

Review materials that you receive today after meeting.

Hold questions. We’ll take questions only at the end of each section.

Stay to very end – through 5 minutes of questions – a question may apply to you.

Agencies appreciate how prepared our students are. This is the first step.

Manageable process for you and for the field office – I can assist those who need it with unforseen problems or unique situations, vs. repeating what was said today.

Positive outcomes: our reputation for prepared students.

You have an impact on this outcome.
CENTRALITY of field education to your development.

Cannot separate the two –

Learning is both in the agency, AND in the classroom - together, these are the field course.

Understand agencies/context for SW practice
Strengthen SW values and ethics
Gain self-awareness and skills in communicating professional judgements
Apply practice methods
Use supervision and feedback

This framework is used throughout field course – assignments, learning goals, evaluation

Often students’ favorite part of MSW education, most memorable

An opportunity to stretch yourself. See your strengths and also your areas for growth.

My own memory of ER in 1991

POWERFUL JOURNEY

A course with specific learning objectives – not volunteer work. Guided by CSWE Accreditation standards.

Has been developing over many years and has grown through input from agencies, faculty, and students.

Pedagogy behind what is done – DRIVEN BY LEARNING – knowledge, skills, values and professional development.

Everything has a reason – please ask.

(Items on this slide will be discussed in next slides)

Field Instructors have been through same experience – MSW practicum.

Expectations and benefits – post this on Canvas site

FITS – purpose

Give and receive consultation. Learn how to have your professional skills impacted by peers, and how to impact others.

Note cohort field seminar schedule.

Evaluate potential agencies for suitability – with standards, with our program priorities, with our curriculum.

Evaluate capacity for supervision – FI who meets credentialing requirements.

Evaluate potential placements (including self-initiated) for suitability – meeting our requirements.

The questions I may ask during this process are intended to ensure that you have a high quality learning experience.

Extra visits could be needed

Foundation is first (unless BSW)

All students do Clinical

How many are going into Foundation?

How many are going into Clinical?

If you don’t know – CONTACT me!
(Description of Generalist comes later)
(Description of Clinical comes later)
Public school settings would expect you to continue until end of school year (early June)

Generalist= sw values, knowledge & skills applicable across all fields of practice

Generalist – person in environment, micro-meso-macro – strengths-based, systems thinking, organizations, professional identity

Even when we’ve been practicing 20 years we still use our generalist skills.

Clinical = a skill set, not a job title. Working at depth over time to learn assessment through closure with populations whose experiences are best addressed with the theoretical frameworks, knowledge and skills you are learning in clinical methods courses.

Applying knowledge of BIO PSYCHO SOCIAL function and differential diagnosis and treatment planning in a variety of settings, including hospitals, schools, mental health settings, etc.

To think diagnostically.

WE HAVE A WIDE RANGE OF PRACTICE SETTINGS FOR BOTH FOUNDATION AND CLINICAL PLACEMENTS

We are going to talk in detail about the steps in getting a placement next
Questions about what we’ve covered so far?
